body:
How do I go about doing this? Show $\frac{d}{dx} \tan^3{x}-3 \tan{x}+3x = 3 \tan^4{x}$. My work. $$
\begin{align*}
\frac{d}{dx} \tan^3 x -3 \tan x+3x 
&= 3 \tan^2 x \sec^2 x - 3 \sec^2 x + 3
\\ &= 3 \frac{\sin^2 x}{\cos^2 x} \frac{1}{\cos^2 x} - 3 \frac{1}{\cos^2 x} + 3
\\ &= 3 \frac{\sin^2 x}{\cos^4 x} - 3 \frac{1}{\cos^2 x} + 3
\\ &= \frac{3\sin^2 x - 3\cos^2 x + 3\cos^4 x}{\cos^4 x} 
\\ &= \frac{3(\sin^2 x - \cos^2 x + \cos^4 x)}{\cos^4 x}. 
\end{align*}
$$ I got here so far, did I make a mistake or something?
